description:
src/lib.rs:189-198 — get() parses the response body into serde_json::Value, then walks it manually:

    let json: serde_json::Value = serde_json::from_slice(&body)?;
    let computed = json
        .get("secret")
        .and_then(|s| s.get("computed"))
        .and_then(|c| c.as_str())
        .ok_or_else(|| SecretError::DecodeFailed(...))?;

The idiomatic Rust pattern is to define a typed deserialization target:

    #[derive(serde::Deserialize)]
    struct DopplerSecretResponse { secret: DopplerSecret }
    #[derive(serde::Deserialize)]
    struct DopplerSecret { computed: String }

then `let parsed: DopplerSecretResponse = serde_json::from_slice(&body)?;` and use `parsed.secret.computed`. Benefits:
  - serde produces a single error message naming the missing field, instead of one generic 'missing secret.computed' string regardless of which field is absent;
  - the response shape is documented in code and grep-able;
  - if Doppler ever returns extra fields (e.g. 'raw', 'note', 'type'), the struct can opt into them without changing call-site code;
  - serde validates types eagerly (e.g. computed: String — if Doppler ever returns a number, the error is precise).

Cost: adds a serde dependency (already present transitively via serde_json). Net win.

Note: Cargo.toml lists serde_json but not serde directly. Adding serde with derive feature is needed.
